{
  "text": "Over the last few years whole genome sequences (WGS) of multiple Staphylococcus aureus strains become available [CITATION_1] . The genetic information coupled with proteomic techniques permit to study S. aureus virulence in previously unavailable details [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . It is widely accepted that staphylococcal pathogenicity is driven by a wide variety of virulence factors rather than single toxins as observed in certain other bacteria. The extracellular and cell wall-associated proteins known as secretome [CITATION_12] and surfacome [CITATION_13] , respectively, are crucial factors enabling host colonization and, subsequently, acute infection [CITATION_14] . The detailed proteome analysis is a powerful tool to explore the interplay of factors responsible for the pathogenicity of bacteria. Indeed, proteomic approach provides a detailed overview of S. aureus cellular processes, helps to uncover the virulence determinants thus allowing to reveal the complexity of the mechanisms of pathogenicity.",
  "correct_citation": {
